fi yields Mg/Ca = 1.043 $\pm$ 0.03 {\^A} e{\textasciicircum}(0.118 $\pm$ 0.1 BWT), r2 = 0.4. Mg/Ca ratios of the porcelaneous epifaunal species Q. arctica show a clear positive relationship between Mg/Ca and D[CO32{\`A}] indicating that this species is not suitable for Mg/Ca-palaeothermometry at low temperatures, but may be useful in reconstructing carbonate system parameters through time.},
