@article{inglisGlobalMeanSurface2020,
	abstract = {{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}strong class="journal-contentHeaderColor"{\textgreater}Abstract.{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} {\textless}span id="page1954"/{\textgreater}Accurate estimates of past global mean surface temperature (GMST) help to contextualise future climate change and are required to estimate the sensitivity of the climate system to {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}CO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} forcing through Earth's history. Previous GMST estimates for the latest Paleocene and early Eocene ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}∼57{\textless}/span{\textgreater} to 48 million years ago) span a wide range ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}∼9{\textless}/span{\textgreater} to 23\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C higher than pre-industrial) and prevent an accurate assessment of climate sensitivity during this extreme greenhouse climate interval. Using the most recent data compilations, we employ a multi-method experimental framework to calculate GMST during the three DeepMIP target intervals: (1) the latest Paleocene ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}∼57{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;Ma), (2) the Paleocene--Eocene Thermal Maximum (PETM; 56\&thinsp;Ma), and (3) the early Eocene Climatic Optimum (EECO; 53.3 to 49.1\&thinsp;Ma). Using six different methodologies, we find that the average GMST estimate (66\&thinsp;\% confidence) during the latest Paleocene, PETM, and EECO was 26.3\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C (22.3 to 28.3\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C), 31.6\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C (27.2 to 34.5\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C), and 27.0\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C (23.2 to 29.7\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C), respectively. GMST estimates from the EECO are {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}∼10{\textless}/span{\textgreater} to 16\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C warmer than pre-industrial, higher than the estimate given by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) 5th Assessment Report (9 to 14\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C higher than pre-industrial). Leveraging the large ``signal'' associated with these extreme warm climates, we combine estimates of GMST and {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}CO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} from the latest Paleocene, PETM, and EECO to calculate gross estimates of the average climate sensitivity between the early Paleogene and today. We demonstrate that ``bulk'' equilibrium climate sensitivity (ECS; 66\&thinsp;\% confidence) during the latest Paleocene, PETM, and EECO is 4.5\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C (2.4 to 6.8\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C), 3.6\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C (2.3 to 4.7\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C), and 3.1\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C (1.8 to 4.4\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C) per doubling of {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}CO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}. These values are generally similar to those assessed by the IPCC (1.5 to 4.5\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{∘}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}C per doubling {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}CO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}) but appear incompatible with low ECS values ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\&lt;1.5{\textless}/span{\textgreater} per doubling {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}CO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}).{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
	author = {Inglis, Gordon N. and Bragg, Fran and Burls, Natalie J. and Cramwinckel, Margot J. and Evans, David and Foster, Gavin L. and Huber, Matthew and Lunt, Daniel J. and Siler, Nicholas and Steinig, Sebastian and Tierney, Jessica E. and Wilkinson, Richard and Anagnostou, Eleni and de Boer, Agatha M. and Dunkley Jones, Tom and Edgar, Kirsty M. and Hollis, Christopher J. and Hutchinson, David K. and Pancost, Richard D.},
