@article{sherwinMixingAdvectionCold2005,
	abstract = {The Wyville Thomson Ridge forms part of the barrier to the meridional circulation across which cold Nordic Sea and Arctic water must traverse to reach the Atlantic Ocean. Overflow rates across the ridge are variable (but can be dramatic at times), and may provide a subtle indicator of significant change in the circulation in response to climate change. In spring 2003, a series of CTD sections were conducted during a large overflow event in which Norwegian Sea Deep Water (NSDW) cascaded down the southern side of the ridge into the Rockall Trough at a rate of between 1 and 2 Sv. The NSDW was partially mixed with overlying North Atlantic Water (NAW), and comprised about 1/3rd of the cascading water. The components of NAW and NSDW in the overflow were sufficiently large that there must have been a significant divergence of the inflow through the Faroe-Shetland Channel, and of the outflow through the Faroe Bank Channel.},
