@article{bradleyThereEvidenceKa2019,
	abstract = {{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}strong class="journal-contentHeaderColor"{\textgreater}Abstract.{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} We review paleoceanographic and paleoclimatic records from the northern North Atlantic to assess the nature of climatic conditions at 4.2\&thinsp;ka\&thinsp;BP, which has been identified as a time of exceptional climatic anomalies in many parts of the world. The northern North Atlantic region experienced relatively warm conditions from 6 to 8\&thinsp;ka\&thinsp;BP, followed by a general decline in temperatures after {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}∼5{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;ka\&thinsp;BP, which led to the onset of neoglaciation. Over the last 5000 years, a series of multi-decadal- to century-scale fluctuations occurred, superimposed on an overall decline in temperature. Although a few records do show a glacial advance around 4.2\&thinsp;ka\&thinsp;BP, because they are not widespread we interpret them as local events -- simply one glacial advance of many that occurred in response to the overall climatic deterioration that characterized the late Holocene.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
