@techreport{degraafMillennialScaleVariability2021,
	abstract = {Climate during the last glacial period was marked by instability on millennial timescales that included rapid changes in Northern Hemisphere sea surface temperatures. Evidence suggests that this millennial-scale variability was a persistent feature of glacials into the Early Pleistocene, when glacial boundary conditions differed considerably from the Late Pleistocene. This project used high-resolution X-ray fluorescence (XRF) analysis to study the millennial-scale variability in the flux of ice-rafted detritus (IRD) and ocean circulation over ODP Sites 980 and 981 on the Feni Drift in the Rockall Trough. By comparison to previous IRD studies at the site, it was shown that a high-pass Zr/Sr ratio can reliably predict periods of increased IRD flux. Moreover, this record was then used to infer a number of ``modes'' of millennial-scale variability during the Pleistocene with transitions at 1.75 Ma, 900 ka and 600 ka. Notably, this project found that changes in the British-Irish Ice Sheet may play a role in the increased IRD flux to the site after MIS 62 (1.75 Ma), and decreased IRD flux to the site after MIS 16 (600 ka). Furthermore, this project used XRF analysis to infer changes in flow speeds over the Feni Drift, at depths of c.2100 m, and from this suggest a stagnant Arctic Ocean may have existed during glacials for the whole Pleistocene. Altogether, this project highlights that high-resolution XRF analysis can provide a rapid, powerful tool to unravel millennial-scale variability across the Pleistocene, identifying regions of interest for further geochemical analysis.},
