@incollection{stowChapterNatureContourite2008,
	abstract = {Publisher Summary
Contourites occur closely interbedded with the other deep-water facies. They range from very fine-grained to relatively coarse-grained deposits and include siliciclastic, bioclastic, volcaniclastic, and chemogenic compositional varieties. This chapter reviews the depositional mechanisms of contourites at the large, intermediate, and small scales. The information derived from drift construction, erosion, sea-floor -bed -form development, and the detail of sediment facies characteristics are considered. It also explores when and where deposition gives way to non-deposition and erosion by bottom currents, and how a long-term accumulation of contourites can result from the alternation of deposition and erosion in time and space. The features and facies of contourites are determined by sedimentary structures, texture, and fabric. The characteristics and principle features of the bottom-current process are schematically represented. Estimated sediment flux from different inputs into the deep -water boundary current that flows over and feeds sediment to the Erik Drift is diagrammatically presented. The average sedimentation rate of contourite deposits varies significantly depending on the location with respect to long-term nature and velocity of the bottom-current system, volume, and source of sediment supply.},
